					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Mea=
sure of the asymmetry of random variables</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">For the plan=
arity measure in graph theory, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Graph_skewness" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Graph skewness">Graph skewn=
ess</a>.</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">

</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:SkewedDistribution.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https=
://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/SkewedDistribution.png=
/216px-SkewedDistribution.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200" height=3D"2=
81" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"216" data-file-height=3D"3=
04"></a><figcaption>Example distribution with positive skewness. These data=
 are from experiments on wheat grass growth.</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Skewness</b> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_=
theory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability theory</a> and <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</=
a> is a measure of the asymmetry of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D"Probability distribution">probabil=
ity distribution</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_num=
ber" title=3D"Real number">real</a>-valued <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random variable</a> abo=
ut its mean. Similarly to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurtosis=
" title=3D"Kurtosis">kurtosis</a>, it provides insights into characteristic=
s of a distribution. The skewness value can be positive, zero, negative, or=
 undefined.
</p><p>For a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unimodal" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Unimodal">unimodal</a> distribution (a distribution wit=
h a single peak), negative skew commonly indicates that the <i>tail</i> is =
on the left side of the distribution, and positive skew indicates that the =
tail is on the right. In cases where one tail is long but the other tail is=
 fat, skewness does not obey a simple rule. For example, a zero value in sk=
ewness means that the tails on both sides of the mean balance out overall; =
this is the case for a symmetric distribution but can also be true for an a=
symmetric distribution where one tail is long and thin, and the other is sh=
ort but fat. Thus, the judgement on the symmetry of a given distribution by=
 using only its skewness is risky; the distribution shape must be taken int=
o account.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Introduction">Introduction<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSkewness&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Introduction"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Consider the two distributions in the figure. Within each graph, the val=
ues on the right side of the distribution taper differently from the values=
 on the left side. These tapering sides are called <i>tails</i>, and they p=
rovide a visual means to determine which of the two kinds of skewness a dis=
tribution has:
</p>
<ol><li><i><span class=3D"vanchor"><span id=3D"negative_skew"></span><span =
class=3D"vanchor-text">negative skew</span></span></i>: The left tail is lo=
nger; the mass of the distribution is concentrated on the right of the figu=
re. The distribution is said to be <i>left-skewed</i>, <i>left-tailed</i>, =
or <i>skewed to the left</i>, despite the fact that the curve itself appear=
s to be skewed or leaning to the right; <i>left</i> instead refers to the l=
eft tail being drawn out and, often, the mean being skewed to the left of a=
 typical center of the data. A left-skewed distribution usually appears as =
a <i>right-leaning</i> curve.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cnx.org_1-0" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness#cite_note-cnx.org-=
1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup></li>
<li><i><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateS=
tyles:r1238216509"><span class=3D"vanchor"><span id=3D"positive_skew"></spa=
n><span class=3D"vanchor-text">positive skew</span></span></i>: The right t=
ail is longer; the mass of the distribution is concentrated on the left of =
the figure. The distribution is said to be <i>right-skewed</i>, <i>right-ta=
iled</i>, or <i>skewed to the right</i>, despite the fact that the curve it=
self appears to be skewed or leaning to the left; <i>right</i> instead refe=
rs to the right tail being drawn out and, often, the mean being skewed to t=
he right of a typical center of the data. A right-skewed distribution usual=
ly appears as a <i>left-leaning</i> curve.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cnx.org_1-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness#cite_=
note-cnx.org-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup></li></ol>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Negative_and_positive_skew_dia=
grams_(English).svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uplo=
ad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Negative_and_positive_skew_di=
agrams_%28English%29.svg/500px-Negative_and_positive_skew_diagrams_%28Engli=
sh%29.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"500" height=3D"178" class=3D"mw-=
file-element" data-file-width=3D"446" data-file-height=3D"159"></a><figcapt=
ion></figcaption></figure><p> Skewness in a data series may sometimes be ob=
served not only graphically but by simple inspection of the values. For ins=
tance, consider the numeric sequence (49, 50, 51), whose values are evenly =
distributed around a central value of 50. We can transform this sequence in=
to a negatively skewed distribution by adding a value far below the mean, w=
hich is probably a negative <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outlie=
r" title=3D"Outlier">outlier</a>, e.g. (40, 49, 50, 51). Therefore, the mea=
n of the sequence becomes 47.5, and the median is 49.5. Based on the formul=
a of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonparametric_skew" title=3D"=
Nonparametric skew">nonparametric skew</a>, defined as <span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline =
mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3=
.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (\mu -\nu )/\sigma ,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>=CE=BC<!-- =CE=BC --></mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>=CE=BD<!-- =CE=BD --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (\mu -\nu )/\=
sigma ,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/8136d7bffb8c7afb5fd3852aecd75f19007f448b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:10.422ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (\=
mu -\nu )/\sigma ,}"></span> the skew is negative. Similarly, we can make t=
he sequence positively skewed by adding a value far above the mean, which i=
s probably a positive outlier, e.g. (49, 50, 51, 60), where the mean is 52.=
5, and the median is 50.5.
</p><p>As mentioned earlier, a unimodal distribution with zero value of ske=
wness does not imply that this distribution is symmetric necessarily. Howev=
er, a symmetric unimodal or multimodal distribution always has zero skewnes=
s.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Asymmetric_Distribution_with_Zero_Skewness.jp=
g" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/w=
ikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Asymmetric_Distribution_with_Zero_Skewness.jpg/=
500px-Asymmetric_Distribution_with_Zero_Skewness.jpg" decoding=3D"async" wi=
dth=3D"434" height=3D"326" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"120=
0" data-file-height=3D"900"></a><figcaption>Example of an asymmetric distri=
bution with zero skewness. This figure serves as a counterexample that zero=
 skewness does not imply symmetric distribution necessarily. (Skewness was =
calculated by Pearson's moment coefficient of skewness.)</figcaption></figu=
re>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relationship_of_mean_and_me=
dian">Relationship of mean and median</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DSkewness&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=
=3D"Edit section: Relationship of mean and median"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The skewness is not directly related to the relationship between the mea=
n and median: a distribution with negative skew can have its mean greater t=
han or less than the median, and likewise for positive skew.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-von_Hippel_2005_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Skewness#cite_note-von_Hippel_2005-2"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Relationship_between_mean_and_median_under_different_skewness.png" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedi=
a/commons/thumb/c/cc/Relationship_between_mean_and_median_under_different_s=
kewness.png/500px-Relationship_between_mean_and_median_under_different_skew=
ness.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"434" height=3D"164" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"1296" data-file-height=3D"489"></a><figcaption>=
A general relationship of mean and median under differently skewed unimodal=
 distribution.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In the older notion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonparam=
etric_skew" title=3D"Nonparametric skew">nonparametric skew</a>, defined as=
 <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mw=
e-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math x=
mlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (\mu =
-\nu )/\sigma ,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mi>=CE=BC<!-- =CE=BC --></mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
