      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CE=BC<!-- =CE=BC --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mu }</annota=
tion>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9fd47b2a39f7a7856952afec1f1db72c67af6161" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:1.402ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \mu=
 }"></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=3D"=
Mean">mean</a>, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display:=
 none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\dis=
playstyle \nu }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CE=BD<!-- =CE=BD --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \nu }</annota=
tion>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c15bbbb971240cf328aba572178f091684585468" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.232ex; height:1.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \nu=
 }"></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median" title=
=3D"Median">median</a>, and <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-elemen=
t-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=
=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" altt=
ext=3D"{\displaystyle \sigma }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \sigma }</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/59f59b7c3e6fdb1d0365a494b81fb9a696138c36" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.33ex; height:1.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \sig=
ma }"></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_devi=
ation" title=3D"Standard deviation">standard deviation</a>, the skewness is=
 defined in terms of this relationship: positive/right nonparametric skew m=
eans the mean is greater than (to the right of) the median, while negative/=
left nonparametric skew means the mean is less than (to the left of) the me=
dian. However, the modern definition of skewness and the traditional nonpar=
ametric definition do not always have the same sign: while they agree for s=
ome families of distributions, they differ in some of the cases, and confla=
ting them is misleading.
</p><p>If the distribution is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symm=
etric_probability_distribution" title=3D"Symmetric probability distribution=
">symmetric</a>, then the mean is equal to the median, and the distribution=
 has zero skewness.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> If the distrib=
ution is both symmetric and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unimod=
al_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unimodal distribution">unim=
odal</a>, then the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=3D"=
Mean">mean</a> =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median" title=
=3D"Median">median</a> =3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_(s=
tatistics)" title=3D"Mode (statistics)">mode</a>. This is the case of a coi=
n toss or the series 1,2,3,4,... Note, however, that the converse is not tr=
ue in general, i.e. zero skewness (defined below) does not imply that the m=
ean is equal to the median.
</p><p>
A 2005 journal article points out:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-von_Hippel_2005_2-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness#cite_=
note-von_Hippel_2005-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p><blockquote><p>Many textbooks teach=
 a rule of thumb stating that the mean is right of the median under right s=
kew, and left of the median under left skew. This rule fails with surprisin=
g frequency. It can fail in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multim=
odal_distribution" title=3D"Multimodal distribution">multimodal distributio=
ns</a>, or in distributions where one tail is <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Long_tail" title=3D"Long tail">long</a> but the other is <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heavy-tailed_distribution" title=3D"Heav=
y-tailed distribution">heavy</a>. Most commonly, though, the rule fails in =
discrete distributions where the areas to the left and right of the median =
are not equal. Such distributions not only contradict the textbook relation=
ship between mean, median, and skew, they also contradict the textbook inte=
rpretation of the median.</p></blockquote>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Positive_skewness_with_mean_less_than_median.png" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4=
/4a/Positive_skewness_with_mean_less_than_median.png/330px-Positive_skewnes=
s_with_mean_less_than_median.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"288" height=
=3D"165" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1081" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"620"></a><figcaption>Distribution of adult residents across US househo=
lds</figcaption></figure>
<p>For example, in the distribution of adult residents across US households=
, the skew is to the right. However, since the majority of cases is less th=
an or equal to the mode, which is also the median, the mean sits in the hea=
vier left tail. As a result, the rule of thumb that the mean is right of th=
e median under right skew failed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-von_Hippel_2005_2-2" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness#cite_n=
ote-von_Hippel_2005-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSkewness&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fisher's_moment_coefficient=
_of_skewness"><span id=3D"Fisher.27s_moment_coefficient_of_skewness"></span=
