</p><p>Examples of distributions with finite skewness include the following=
.
</p>
<ul><li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" tit=
le=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a> and any other symmetric =
distribution with finite third moment has a skewness of 0</li>
<li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-normal_distribution" ti=
tle=3D"Half-normal distribution">half-normal distribution</a> has a skewnes=
s just below 1</li>
<li>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_distribution" t=
itle=3D"Exponential distribution">exponential distribution</a> has a skewne=
ss of 2</li>
<li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lognormal_distribution" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lognormal distribution">lognormal distribution</=
a> can have a skewness of any positive value, depending on its parameters</=
li></ul>
