an">median</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_(statistic=
s)" title=3D"Mode (statistics)">mode</a> of two <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Log-normal_distribution" title=3D"Log-normal distribution">lo=
g-normal distributions</a> with the same medians and different skewnesses.<=
/figcaption></figure>
<p>Other measures of skewness have been used, including simpler calculation=
s suggested by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Pearson" title=
=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl Pearson</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Capistrano1_10-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness#cite_not=
e-Capistrano1-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (not to be confused with Pearson's moment coe=
fficient of skewness, see above). These other measures are:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pearson's_first_skewness_co=
efficient_(mode_skewness)"><span id=3D"Pearson.27s_first_skewness_coefficie=
nt_.28mode_skewness.29"></span>Pearson's first skewness coefficient (mode s=
kewness)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSke=
wness&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Pearson's f=
irst skewness coefficient (mode skewness)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Pearson mode skewness,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness#cite_note-11"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 or first skewness coefficient, is defined as
</p>
<div class=3D"block-indent" style=3D"padding-left: 1.5em;"><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:125%;"><span class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span c=
lass=3D"num"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean" title=3D"Mean">=
mean</a> =E2=88=92 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_(statistic=
s)" title=3D"Mode (statistics)">mode</a></span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</s=
pan><span class=3D"den"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_d=
eviation" title=3D"Standard deviation">standard deviation</a></span></span>=
=E2=81=A0</span></span>.</div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Pearson's_second_skewness_c=
oefficient_(median_skewness)"><span id=3D"Pearson.27s_second_skewness_coeff=
icient_.28median_skewness.29"></span>Pearson's second skewness coefficient =
(median skewness)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DSkewness&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: P=
earson's second skewness coefficient (median skewness)"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Pearson median skewness, or second skewness coefficient,<sup id=3D"c=
